{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506522"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2546"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2546"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.1,0.48,0.12,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39581"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2546"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24037"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"668"},{"type":"tags","id":"1098"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2570"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39581"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with weakness and tingling in her extremities for the past several days. She has had multiple episodes of nephrolithiasis in the past. She also reports dryness of the eyes and the mouth for the past year. She does not have diarrhoea and does not take any medications. On examination her blood pressure is 135/80 mmHg, pulse 83/min and temperature 37.1 C. She has generalised muscle weakness and her deep tendon reflexes are decreased. Serum electrolyte laboratory results are shown below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium = 139 mmol/L (135-145 mmol/L)\u003Cbr /\u003EChloride = 112 mmol/L (101-110 mmol/L)\u003Cbr /\u003EPotassium = 2.6 mmol/L (3.5-5.2 mmol/L)\u003Cbr /\u003EBicarbonate = 17 mmol/L (22-32 mmol/L)\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EAn arterial blood gas (ABG) analysis is ordered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings will most likely be seen on her ABG?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["pH 7.35, pCO2 31, elevated serum anion gap","pH 7.4, pCO2 40, normal serum anion gap","pH 7.32, pCO2 29, normal serum anion gap","pH 7.45, pCO2 30, normal serum anion gap","pH 7.34, pCO2 48, normal serum anion gap"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u2019s muscle weakness is most likely due to hypokalaemia. Her serum electrolytes showing low bicarbonate and elevated chloride are suggestive of normal anion-gap (hyperchloraemic) metabolic acidosis. The most likely underlying cause of her normal anion-gap metabolic acidosis is renal tubular acidosis (RTA) type 1\u003Cstrong\u003E. \u003C/strong\u003ERTA type 1 can be idiopathic but may also be associated with autoimmune conditions (eg, Sjogren syndrome, systemic lupus erythematosus). On the other hand, familial type 1 RTA usually presents growth retardation and failure to thrive in childhood. Among all the types of RTA, RTA type 1 is the only one associated with recurrent nephrolithiasis. This patient\u2019s history of recurrent nephrolithiasis and dryness of mouth and eyes (ie, Sjogren syndrome) raises the risk of RTA type 1. Metabolic acidosis leads to respiratory compensation by increased CO2 removal. This leads to decreased pCO2 on arterial blood gas analysis. Since RTA is associated with normal anion-gap metabolic acidosis, the most likely finding among the answer choices that will be seen in this patient will be \u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.32, pCO2 29, normal serum anion gap\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.35, pCO2 31, elevated serum anion gap\u003C/strong\u003E ABG finding is seen in conditions that cause elevated anion-gap metabolic acidosis (eg, lactic acidosis, uremia, diabetic ketoacidosis). It is not associated with elevated chloride.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.4, pCO2 40, normal serum anion gap\u003C/strong\u003E is a normal ABG finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.45, pCO2 30, normal serum anion gap\u003C/strong\u003E ABG finding is seen in patients with respiratory alkalosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.34, pCO2 48, normal serum anion gap\u003C/strong\u003E ABG finding is seen in patients with respiratory acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Muscle weakness is a key symptom of hypokalaemia."],"references":["Yaxley J, Pirrone C. Review of the Diagnostic Evaluation of Renal Tubular Acidosis. Ochsner J. 2016 Winter;16(4):525-530."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24037"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2546"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24037"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-09-26T20:01:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-12T19:54:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2546"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39581"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"